<h1><font color="#00868B">Panel: </font color>
<i>When Ontogeny Inverts Phylogeny: <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp 
Regulation in a Fully-Connected World?</i></h1>

<h1> <font color="#00868B">Panelist/Moderator: </font color></h1>


<h2> Michael M. Krieger, Bronson, Bronson & McKinnon LLP</h2>

Michael M. Krieger is a Los Angeles attorney whose practice is devoted
to computer, communication and high technology business transactions and
strategic intellectual property protection, especially for software and
Internet-related development, acquisition and licensing.  He is a
frequent speaker and author on computer law/business topics, including domain
name/trademark tensions, cryptographic policy, and software contracting.
Mr. Krieger chairs the Computer Law Committee of the California Bar's
Intellectual Property Section and is an editor of the Section's journal,
New Matter.
<p> 
With degrees from Caltech (B.S.) and UCLA (Ph.D.), Mr. Krieger spent
15 years on the computer science and mathematics faculties of UCLA, MIT,
and, as a Fulbright Scholar, UFMG, Brazil, prior to receiving a J.D.
from UCLA and joining the California Bar.   Mr. Krieger is Of Counsel to
Bronson, Bronson & McKinnon, LLP.

<h1><font color="#00868B">Panelists:</font color></h1>

<h2>Michael D. Scott, Perkins Coie LLP (Los Angeles and Menlo Park,
California) </h2>

Michael D. Scott received his B.S. in mathematics from the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology in 1967, and spent six  years doing software system
design at the MIT Computation Center, NASA-Electronics Research Lab,
Computer Sciences Corporation and Univac before entering law school.  He
graduated with a J.D. from UCLA in 1974.

<p> 

Mr. Scott has spent the last 24 years practicing computer law.  He has
extensive experience in intellectual property matters, particularly as they
apply to computer software, licensing, international transactions,
multimedia and Internet law.  He is author of "Scott on Computer Law" (2d
edition), "Scott on Multimedia Law" (2d ed.), and co-author of "The Year
2000 Computer Crisis:  Law, Business, Technology (1998).  He is also
Editor-in-chief of the "Cyberspace Lawyer" and "E-Commerce Law Report"
newsletters.

<p> 

Mr. Scott is a member of the Board of Directors of the Computer Law
Association and Chairman of the annual Cyberspace Law School conference and
the Year 2000 Legal Issues conference.
 
<h2> Clark Savage Turner, UC Irvine</h2>

Clark Savage Turner holds a B.S. (math, 1979) and an M.A. 
(math, 1981). While teaching mathematics and programming, he studied law, 
receiving his J.D. (1986). While practicing law in 1988 and 1989, he 
worked with Nancy Leveson investigating the Therac-25 accidents and went
on to receive an M.S. (Information and Computer Science, 1992). He now 
studies with Professor Debra Richardson in the area of Software Engineering 
at the University of California, Irvine where he expects to receive his
Ph.D. during the coming year.

